'''Florence Nwanzuruahu Nkiru Nwapa''' (<small>abodin: </small><span class="IPA nopopups">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="/ˈ/ primary stress follows">ˈ</span><span title="'f' in 'find'">f</span><span title="'l' in 'lie'">l</span><span title="/ɔː/ 'au' in 'fraud'">ɔː</span><span title="'r' in 'rye'">r</span><span title="/ə/ 'a' in 'about'">ə</span></span>/</span>{{IPAc-en|pron|ˈ|f|l|ɔː|r|ə}} <span class="IPA nopopups">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="/ŋ/ 'ng' in 'sing'">ŋ</span><span title="/ˈ/ primary stress follows">ˈ</span><span title="'w' in 'wind'">w</span><span title="/oʊ/ long 'o' in 'code'">oʊ</span><span title="'p' in 'pie'">p</span><span title="/ɑː/ 'a' in 'father'">ɑː</span></span>/</span>{{IPAc-en|ŋ|ˈ|w|oʊ|p|ɑː}}) (13  Ɔpɛpɔn 1931 – 16 Ahinime 1993) a na wɔtae frɛ no '''Flora Nwapa''', na ɔyɛ Alata ni baa wɔ hu no ɔkandifo sɛ ɛba no nwoma atwerɛAfrican literature. Wɔyɛ ɔbaa ɔdi kan sɛ ɛba no Enyiresi [[Brɔfo]] nwoma twerɛ  na ɔnyaa abɔdin  wɔ ɛho ,<ref name="DofA">[//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Busby Margaret Busby], "Flora Nwapa", ''[//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daughters_of_Africa:_An_International_Anthology_of_Words_and_Writings_by_Women_of_African_Descent Daughters of Africa: An International Anthology of Words and Writings by Women of African Descent]'' (1992), Vintage: 1993, p. 399.</ref> ne nwoma a  ɛdi kan ''Efuru'' baa afe 1966 Heinemann Educational Books na otimtim. Na wonhu ne ho sɛ  obi a na ɔreko ma mmaa mputuo nso  ɔgyee ne din wɔ san kwan yi so aberɛ  ɔresesa kwan a Ibo mmaa hunu nneɛma .<ref name="Emory">Susan Leisure, [https://scholarblogs.emory.edu/postcolonialstudies/2014/06/11/nwapa-flora/ "Nwapa, Flora"], Postcolonial Studies @ Emory, Emory University, Fall 1996.</ref>

Nwapa nso ka wɔn a ɔmo boa ma osisie [[Alata]] ɛberɛ a Biafra ntɔkwa no twaa. Wɔne nnyanka ɛne nkurofoɔ ntɔkwa no nti wɔn ni baabi te na ɛyɛɛ adwuma.  Afei nso ɔtwerɛ nnwoma bebree a ɛboa >[[Abibre]] mmaa mputuo .<ref name="litencyc">[http://www.litencyc.com/php/speople.php?rec=true&UID=3364 Literary Encyclopedia]</ref> Na ɔyɛ obaa ɔdi kan aberɛ a wobue '''Tana Press   '''wɔ''' '''afe''' '''1970s.

=== Mfe edikan ne nwomasua ===
Wɔwoo Nwapa wɔ  Oguta,<ref name="born">Hamilton, Janice, ''Nigeria in Pictures'', p. 71.</ref> ,ɛwɔ  Alata  anafoɔ-apue na ɔye piese ma   Owura Krisofa  Igyeoma  ( ɔdwumani wɔ United Africa Company) ne Mata Nwapa,  ɔkyerɛkyerɛni a ɔkyerɛ yikyerɛ wɔn mma nsia no mu  .<ref>[http://www.informationng.com/2013/03/interesting-things-about-flora-nwapa-nigerias-first-female-novelist.html "Interesting Things About Flora Nwapa, Nigeria’s First Female Novelist"], Information Nigeria, 1 March 2013.</ref> Flora Nwapa kɔɔ sukuu wɔ Oguta, Port Harcourt ne [[Lagos]]. Flora nyaa na abodin  BA degree wɔ [[Ibadan]] Suapɔn mu, wɔ afe1957. Afei ɔkɔɔ  Skotland  kɔɔ sukuu wɔ [[Endibra Suapɔn]] mu na ɔnyaa abɔdin  Diploma in Education from wɔ afe 1958.

=== Adekyerɛ ne Abandwuma ===
 Nwapa firi Enyiresi baa Alata  no ɔhy aduma ase wɔ Nwomasua Asoeɛ  wɔ [[Kalaba]] sɛ Nwomasua Dwumayɛni kɔsi afe  1959. Afei ɔbɛyɛɛ ɔkyerɛkyerɛni wɔ Queen's School in [[Enug]]u, wɔkyerɛɛ firi afe 1959)

=== Atwerɛ ===
Nwapa nwoma a ɛdi , ''Efuru'', baa afe 1966 na wohu saa nwoma sɛ ɛyɛ adikanfo sɛ brofo nwoma a Abibire mu ɔbaa twerɛ. Saa nwoma yi  ɔde Alata ni barima a na ɔno nso ɔtwerɛnwoma a na wagye ne din a wɔfrɛ no [[Chinua Akyebɛ]]  wɔ afe1962.  Akyebɛ nso di anigyeɛ twerɛɛ de sika mpo mane no sɛ wonfa nkɔ ma wɔn adumakuo  Heinemann wɔtimtim krataa wɔ brɔfo mu .<ref>[http://www.thejournalist.org.za/books/flora-nwapa-and-the-letter-that-changed-nigerian-literature-forever Ainehi Edoro, Flora Nwapa and the Letter That Changed Nigerian Literature Forever], thejournalist.org.za, retrieved March 2017</ref><ref>[https://books.google.de/books?id=ZTNOEimkkEcC&pg=PA93&lpg=PA93&dq=Nwapa+chinua+abebe&source=bl&ots=HewoIprKIq&sig=_TCOl6NkgMjjbhFaF4F0dIwvfms&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj99aP3t73SAhVDuhQKHSEGBFkQ6AEIOzAF#v=onepage&q=Nwapa%20chinua%20abebe&f=false Ezenwa-Ohaeto, Chinua Achebe: A Biography],p. 93, ISBN 0253333423 (ISBN 9780253333421), via google-books</ref>

Wei akyiri no ɔtwerɛɛ Idu (1970), ''Never Again'' (1975), ''One is Enough'' (1981), and ''Women Are Different'' Wɔtwerɛɛ (1986) nwoma mmienu a na ɛwɔ anansesɛm bebree   {{snd}}''This Is Lagos'' (1971) and ''Wives at War'' (1980) {{snd}}and the volume of poems ''Cassava Song and Rice Song'' (1986).  Watwerɛ mmofra anasesem bebree.

Afe 1974 wɔtee Tana  Press wɔ 1977 wɔtee Nwapa Company, a  detwerɛ mmofra anasesem bebree a na  ɛyɛ ɔnoa na atwerɛ ne nea amanfoɔ  atwerɛ .<ref>Hans M. Zell, [http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0006/000609/060911mb.pdf "Publishing and Book Development in Africa: A Bibliography"] (''Studies on Books and Reading'', UNESCO), p.&nbsp;{{nbsp}}4.</ref> Botae a na ɛsi n'ani so ne sɔ  ɔbekyerɛ mmaa ne wɔn aɔko ma mmaa yidie.  (both with capital F and mall f) about the role of women in Nigeria, their economic independence, their relationship with their husbands and children, their traditional beliefs and their status in the community as a whole".<ref>"Frankfurt Book Fair 1980", Flora Nwapa interviewed in ''The African Book Publishing Record'', Vol.</ref> Tana has been described as "the first press run by a woman and targeted at a largely female audience. A project far beyond its time at a period when no one saw African women as constituting a community of readers or a book-buying demographic."<ref>[http://brittlepaper.com/2016/02/flora-nwapa#sthash.lY3eP9lF.dpuf "Flora Nwapa and the Letter That Changed Nigerian Literature Forever"], Brittle Paper, 3&nbsp;{{nbsp}}February 2016.</ref>

=== Mfie a etwa to ===
Nwapa adekyerɛ adwuman no toa so aberɛ a ɔkokyerɛ wɔ kɔ  kyerɛ adeɛ wɔ Suapɔn bebree mu ɛbi ne  New York University, Trinity College{{dn|date=September 2016}}, the University of Minnesota, the University of Michigan and the University of Ilorin.

Flora Nwapa wuie wɔ  Ahimime bosome da 1 6 wɔ afe  1993 wɔ  Enugu Ayaresabea,wɔ Alata  na wadi mfie 62 Awɔ yareɛ na ɛkum no .<ref>Brenda F, Berrian, [http://www.jstor.org/stable/3174890?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents "In Memoriam: Flora Nwapa (1931–1993"], ''Signs'', Vol.&nbsp;{{nbsp}}20, No.&nbsp;{{nbsp}}4, ''Postcolonial, Emergent, and Indigenous Feminisms'' (Summer 1995), pp.&nbsp;{{nbsp}}996–999.</ref>

